## Alternative Metals: Tantalum and Why Platinum Wins

Tantalum is a refractory metal with a distinctive dark grey or black appearance. Blue Nile carries two tantalum diamond options:
- [Satin Finish Diamond Wedding Ring Grey Tantalum 7.5mm 3/8 ct — $1,319 (sale)](https://www.bluenile.com/wedding-rings/satin-finish-diamond-wedding-ring-in-grey-tantalum-75-mm-3-8-ct-tw-item-192431?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)
- [Satin Finish Black Diamond Wedding Ring Dark Tantalum 7.5mm 3/8 ct — $1,885](https://www.bluenile.com/wedding-rings/satin-finish-black-diamond-wedding-ring-in-dark-tantalum-75-mm-3-8-ct-tw-item-192430?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)

Tantalum is biocompatible, lighter than platinum, and scratch-resistant. The dark grey tone is unique and pairs well with industrial aesthetics. The limitation: tantalum cannot be resized after setting. If your ring size changes significantly, the ring becomes unusable. Tantalum can be cut off in a medical emergency (unlike tungsten, which cannot), so it passes the safety test.

Platinum wins as the daily wear choice for most buyers because it can be resized, repaired, and re-polished indefinitely. The [Diagonal Lined Pavé Edge Platinum at $1,526](https://www.bluenile.com/wedding-rings/diagonal-lined-with-pave-diamond-edge-mens-wedding-ring-in-platinum-1-8-ct-tw-item-196082?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) costs only $207 more than the tantalum option and is a lifetime-serviceable ring. For buyers who specifically want the dark metal aesthetic, tantalum is the correct choice — but go in with full awareness of the no-resize limitation.

